## Living Design 3.5 — Design System Rules

### Layout Rules

- **Never use `max-width` constraints** on page content containers. All page content (headers, content areas) must fill the full available width within the sidebar + masthead shell.
- **Use `align-items: stretch`** instead of `align-items: center` on flex column containers that hold page content. Centering causes content to shrink instead of filling width.
- **Standard page shell pattern** — every page must use this identical structure:

```tsx
<div className={styles.root}>       {/* full viewport, flex column */}
  <MastHead />
  <div className={styles.appRow}>   {/* flex row: sidebar + main */}
    <AppSidebar menuItems={...} />
    <main className={styles.main}>  {/* flex: 1, overflow-y: auto */}
      {/* page content here */}
    </main>
  </div>
</div>
```

- Content areas should use `flex: 1` to expand and fill available height.

### Token Rules (CRITICAL)

- **Never use hardcoded hex colors.** Always use `var(--ld-semantic-color-*)` tokens with hex fallbacks:

```css
/* ✅ CORRECT */
color: var(--ld-semantic-color-text, #2E2F32);
background: var(--ld-semantic-color-background-subtle, #f8f8f8);

/* ❌ WRONG */
color: #2E2F32;
background: #F8F8F8;
```

- **Background surfaces**:
  - Page background: `--ld-semantic-color-background-subtle`
  - Cards/panels: `--ld-semantic-color-surface`
  - Hover states: `--ld-semantic-color-surface-hovered`
  - Overlays/dropdowns: `--ld-semantic-color-surface-overlay`

- **Text hierarchy**:
  - Primary: `--ld-semantic-color-text`
  - Secondary: `--ld-semantic-color-text-subtle`
  - Tertiary: `--ld-semantic-color-text-subtlest`
  - Brand: `--ld-semantic-color-text-brand`

- **Sentiment colors** — apply to BOTH text AND icons:
  - Negative/error: `--ld-semantic-color-text-negative` (never hardcode red)
  - Positive/success: `--ld-semantic-color-text-positive` (never hardcode green)

- **Ratings**: Use `--ld-semantic-color-rating-fill` and `--ld-semantic-color-rating-border`, never hardcode `#FFC220`.

- **Borders/separators**: `--ld-semantic-color-separator` for dividers, `--ld-semantic-color-border-strong` for input borders.

### Component Rules

- **HARD RULE: Always use existing design system components.** Never create new custom components when an existing one in `client/components/ui/` already covers the need. Search `client/components/ui/` and `design-system-docs/` FIRST. This applies to all UI elements — buttons, tags, tabs, tables, selects, modals, etc.
- **HARD RULE: NEVER modify existing design system components. NO EXCEPTIONS.** Do not edit, override, or alter any component source file in `client/components/ui/`. This applies especially to LD (Living Design) components — they are the canonical source of truth and must remain untouched. No adding props, no changing styles, no editing CSS modules, no adding variants to existing files. If a user requests a modification to an existing component's look or behavior:
  1. **Do NOT edit the original component file.**
  2. **Create a new variant** as a separate shared component in `client/components/ui/` that composes or wraps the original. For example, if the user wants a card with a special header, create `CardWithHeader.tsx` that wraps `Card` — do not modify `Card.tsx`.
  3. The new variant becomes a reusable shared component available to the entire project.
  4. Document the new variant in `guidelines/` so other pages can discover and use it.
- **HARD RULE: Never create a new sidebar or side navigation.** Always reuse the existing `AppSidebar` component (`client/components/ui/AppSidebar.tsx`). When building a new page, import and render `AppSidebar` — only replace the `menuItems` content (labels, icons, links) to match the page's needs. Do not create a new `<aside>`, `<nav>`, or custom sidebar component. The sidebar structure, styling, collapse/expand behavior, and layout are already handled by `AppSidebar` and must stay consistent across all pages.
- **Import paths** — ALL components use PascalCase file names:

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — PascalCase for everything
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/Button';
import { ButtonGroup } from '@/components/ui/ButtonGroup';
import { Tag } from '@/components/ui/Tag';
import { Rating } from '@/components/ui/Rating';
import { Dialog, DialogContent, DialogTrigger } from '@/components/ui/Dialog';
import { Popover, PopoverTrigger, PopoverContent } from '@/components/ui/Popover';
import { ScrollArea } from '@/components/ui/ScrollArea';
import { Tooltip, TooltipContent, TooltipTrigger } from '@/components/ui/Tooltip';

// ❌ WRONG — lowercase file names no longer exist
import { Dialog } from '@/components/ui/dialog';
import { Popover } from '@/components/ui/popover';
import { ScrollArea } from '@/components/ui/scroll-area';
```

- **Rating stars**: Use `<Rating value={4.4} size="small" />`, never manually render star SVGs.
- **Buttons**: Always use `<Button variant="primary|secondary|tertiary|destructive" size="small|medium|large">`. Never create `<button>` elements with inline styles.
- **Button width MUST match Figma intent (HARD RULE)**:
  - If a button **hugs its text** in Figma (width fits the label), use the default Button behavior — do NOT add `isFullWidth`, do NOT add `width: 100%`, do NOT add any width overrides. The button's `inline-flex` display naturally hugs its content.
  - If a button is **full-width** in Figma (stretches across its container), use `<Button isFullWidth>`. This sets `width: 100%`.
  - **Never force button widths with inline styles, custom classes, or `UNSAFE_style`.** The only two width modes are: default (hug text) and `isFullWidth` (stretch). No in-between, no fixed pixel widths, no percentage widths other than 100%.
  - When in doubt, default to hug text (no `isFullWidth`).
- **Tags**: Use `<Tag variant="..." color="...">`, never `<span>` with custom badge styles.
- **Button groups**: Use `<ButtonGroup>`, never manual flex containers for buttons.
- **Checkboxes**: Always use `<Checkbox>` from `@/components/ui/Checkbox`. Never create custom checkbox elements with `<input type="checkbox">`, styled divs, or SVG toggles.
- **Radios**: Always use `<Radio>` from `@/components/ui/Radio` and `<RadioGroup>` from `@/components/ui/RadioGroup`. Never create custom radio elements with `<input type="radio">`, styled circles, or custom toggle groups.

#### Checkbox & Radio (HARD RULE)

- **NEVER create custom checkbox or radio components.** Always use the existing LD components.
- **Always use large checkboxes for confirmation messages.** Any confirmation dialog, terms acceptance, consent flow, or prominent single-checkbox interaction must use `size="large"`. The default `small` size is for data tables, filters, and multi-select lists.
```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — large checkbox for confirmations
import { Checkbox } from '@/components/ui/Checkbox';
<Checkbox size="large" label="I confirm this action" checked={confirmed} onCheckedChange={setConfirmed} />

// ✅ CORRECT — small checkbox (default) for lists, filters, tables
<Checkbox label="Select item" checked={checked} onCheckedChange={setChecked} />

// ✅ CORRECT — use LD Radio and RadioGroup
import { Radio } from '@/components/ui/Radio';
import { RadioGroup } from '@/components/ui/RadioGroup';
<RadioGroup value={selected} onValueChange={setSelected}>
  <Radio value="option1" label="Option 1" />
  <Radio value="option2" label="Option 2" />
</RadioGroup>

// ❌ WRONG — custom checkbox with styled input
<input type="checkbox" className="custom-check" />

// ❌ WRONG — div pretending to be a checkbox
<div className="w-4 h-4 border rounded" onClick={toggle}>✓</div>

// ❌ WRONG — custom radio with styled input
<input type="radio" name="group" className="custom-radio" />

// ❌ WRONG — custom toggle group pretending to be radios
<div className="flex gap-2">
  <button className={active === 'a' ? 'selected' : ''}>A</button>
  <button className={active === 'b' ? 'selected' : ''}>B</button>
</div>
```

#### Links (HARD RULE)

- **NEVER create raw `<a>` tags or custom hyperlink styles.** All text links MUST use the LD `Link` component from `client/components/ui/Link.tsx`.
- The Link component handles LD 3.5 tokens (`--ld-semantic-color-link-text-*`), underline behavior, hover/focus/active states, and accessibility automatically.
- **Variants**: `default` (brand-colored), `subtle` (gray), `white` (for dark backgrounds).
- Auto-detects internal vs external links — internal links use React Router, external links get `rel="noreferrer noopener"` when `target="_blank"`.
- **Import pattern**:
```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — use LD Link component
import { Link } from '@/components/ui/Link';

<Link href="/settings">Account settings</Link>
<Link href="https://example.com" target="_blank">External site</Link>
<Link href="/help" variant="subtle">Help</Link>

// ❌ WRONG — raw anchor tag
<a href="/settings">Account settings</a>

// ❌ WRONG — styled span pretending to be a link
<span className="text-blue-500 underline cursor-pointer" onClick={...}>Click here</span>

// ❌ WRONG — hardcoded link colors
<a href="/page" style={{ color: '#0053e2', textDecoration: 'underline' }}>Link</a>
```

#### DataTable (HARD RULE — NO EXCEPTIONS)

- **NEVER create custom/hardcoded `<table>` elements.** All tabular data MUST use the existing DataTable component system from `client/components/ui/DataTable*.tsx`.
- Available DataTable components: `DataTable`, `DataTableHead`, `DataTableBody`, `DataTableRow`, `DataTableHeader`, `DataTableCell`, `DataTableCellText`, `DataTableCellSelect`, `DataTableCellStatus`, `DataTableCellActions`, `DataTableCellInlineEdit`, `DataTableCellBulkEdit`, `DataTableBulkActions`, `DataTableTitle`, `DataTableConfigPanel`.
- **New cell variants are allowed** — you may create new `DataTableCell*` components that follow the existing pattern (CSS module + forwardRef + CommonProps). But you may NOT create a net-new table structure outside the DataTable system.
- **Always round DataTable frames** — but the rounding comes from the correct layer:
  - **Standalone DataTable** (not inside a card): pass `rounded` on the DataTable itself.
  - **DataTable inside a card or container**: the outer card/wrapper provides the rounded frame with `border-radius` and `border`. Do NOT set `rounded` on the DataTable — it creates ugly double-rounding. Use a wrapper like `.tableCard` with its own `border-radius` and `overflow: hidden` instead.
- **NEVER customize DataTable colors or visual styling.** DataTable must look identical everywhere it appears — same header background, same row colors, same borders, same text styles. Even if a Figma design shows alternate row colors, tinted headers, colored backgrounds, striped rows, or any other visual variation, **ignore those differences and use the default DataTable styling**. The canonical styling is defined in `DataTable.module.css` and must not be overridden or extended with:
  - Custom background colors on headers, rows, or cells
  - Alternate/striped row coloring
  - Tinted or colored header backgrounds
  - Custom border colors or styles
  - Custom font colors, sizes, or weights beyond the built-in `textStyle` prop (`body-small` or `body-medium`)
  - Any `UNSAFE_className` or `UNSAFE_style` overrides that change visual appearance
  - Figma-specific color tokens or one-off design treatments
- **Import pattern**:
```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — use DataTable components
import { DataTable, DataTableHead, DataTableBody } from '@/components/ui/DataTable';
import { DataTableRow } from '@/components/ui/DataTableRow';
import { DataTableHeader } from '@/components/ui/DataTableHeader';
import { DataTableCell } from '@/components/ui/DataTableCellText';

// ❌ WRONG — custom hardcoded table
<table className="my-table"><tr><td>...</td></tr></table>

// ❌ WRONG — div-based grid pretending to be a table
<div className="grid grid-cols-4">...</div> // for tabular data
```

#### Overlays (HARD RULE — Popovers, Dropdowns, Tooltips, Dialogs)

- **All overlay elements MUST render on top of everything and NEVER be clipped or cut off.** This includes popovers, dropdown menus, tooltips, select menus, dialogs, and any floating UI.
- **Always use LD portal-based components** (`Popover`, `DropdownMenu`, `Dialog`, `Tooltip`, `Select`) from `client/components/ui/` — these portal content to `document.body`, ensuring they escape any `overflow: hidden` or `overflow: auto` ancestors.
- **Never set `overflow: hidden` on containers that hold overlay triggers** unless the overlay portals out. If you must use `overflow: hidden` (e.g., for a scrollable card or table wrapper), ensure the overlay component portals its content outside that container.
- **Z-index**: Overlay content should use the standard z-index scale. Never set arbitrary z-index values. LD overlay components handle this automatically — do not override their z-index.
- **Common mistakes that cause clipping**:
  - Parent container has `overflow: hidden` or `overflow: auto` and the overlay does not portal out
  - Missing `position: relative` or incorrect stacking context
  - Using custom dropdown/popover implementations instead of LD components
  - Setting `z-index` too low on overlay content
- **If an overlay appears cut off**, the fix is almost always one of:
  1. Use the LD portal-based component (which portals automatically)
  2. Remove unnecessary `overflow: hidden` from ancestor containers
  3. Never restrict `overflow` on the direct parent of a trigger without portaling

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — LD Popover portals to body, always on top
import { Popover, PopoverTrigger, PopoverContent } from '@/components/ui/Popover';
<Popover>
  <PopoverTrigger>Open</PopoverTrigger>
  <PopoverContent>Always visible, never clipped</PopoverContent>
</Popover>

// ✅ CORRECT — LD DropdownMenu portals to body
import { DropdownMenu, DropdownMenuTrigger, DropdownMenuContent } from '@/components/ui/DropdownMenu';

// ❌ WRONG — custom dropdown inside overflow:hidden parent gets clipped
<div style={{ overflow: 'hidden' }}>
  <div className="custom-dropdown">This will be cut off!</div>
</div>

// ❌ WRONG — custom absolute-positioned menu without portal
<div style={{ position: 'relative' }}>
  <button>Toggle</button>
  <div style={{ position: 'absolute', top: '100%' }}>Menu items...</div>
</div>
```

#### Tabs (HARD RULE)

- **NEVER create custom tab components.** Always use the existing `Tab` component from `client/components/ui/Tab.tsx`.
- Available exports: `Tabs`, `TabList`, `Tab`, `TabPanel`.
- **Import pattern**:
```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT
import { Tabs, TabList, Tab, TabPanel } from '@/components/ui/Tab';

// ❌ WRONG — custom tab implementation
<div className="tab-bar">
  <button className="tab active">Tab 1</button>
</div>
```

### Styling Rules

- **Always use CSS Modules** (`.module.css`), never inline `style={{}}` for layout or colors.
- Inline styles are only acceptable for truly dynamic values (e.g., calculated widths).
- **Standard spacing**: Use 8px multiples (8, 16, 24, 32, 48px). Use `var(--ld-semantic-spacing-*)` or `var(--ld-primitive-scale-space-*)` tokens when available.
- **Responsive breakpoints** (standard across all pages):
  - `1024px` — tablet
  - `768px` — small tablet
  - `480px` — phone
  - Padding reduces: `24px → 16px → 12px` across breakpoints
- **Font family**: Always `var(--ld-semantic-font-family-sans)` or specific semantic font tokens like `var(--ld-semantic-font-heading-large-family)`. Never let text fall back to browser serif defaults.
- **Border radius**: Use `var(--ld-primitive-scale-borderradius-100, 8px)` for cards, `9999px` for pills/circles.
- **Box shadows** for elevated cards: `0 -1px 2px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.10), 0 1px 2px 1px rgba(0,0,0,0.15)`.

### Designer Getting Started — Figma Best Practices (HARD RULES)

These rules ensure Figma designs translate cleanly into code. Designers MUST follow these before handing off:

1. **Always use Auto Layout in Figma.** Every frame must use Auto Layout — never use absolute positioning or free-floating layers. Auto Layout translates directly to CSS flexbox, making implementation accurate and responsive. Frames without Auto Layout produce broken, absolute-positioned code.

2. **Always make images exportable — never use placeholders.** Every image and illustration in Figma must be marked as exportable (right panel → Export section → add an export setting). If an image exists in Figma, it must be exported and used in the implementation. **Never replace Figma images with gray boxes, placeholder rectangles, or generic stock images.** The actual image asset from Figma is the source of truth and must appear in the final code.

3. **Be explicit in your annotations.** Add clear annotations in Figma for all interactions, hover states, click behaviors, navigation targets, error states, loading states, and conditional logic. The more explicit your annotations, the fewer prompts are needed and the more accurate the implementation. Don't assume the AI will infer behavior — spell it out.

4. **Name your layers and artboards sequentially.** Use clear, sequential naming for screens and layers (e.g., `01-Landing`, `02-Catalog`, `03-Detail`, or `Step1-Login`, `Step2-Verify`). This helps when exporting multiple screens and ensures the AI processes them in the correct order.

5. **All screens must hug content — never clip.** Every screen/frame must be set to "Hug Contents" so all content is visible. Do not use "Clip Content" to hide overflow — if content is clipped in Figma, the AI cannot see or implement the hidden portions. Even if you temporarily unclip to preview, the final handoff frame must show all content without clipping.

6. **Use LD Components — do not fake them.** Always use actual Living Design component instances from the LD 3.5 library. Do not group primitive shapes/layers to visually mimic an LD component (e.g., grouping rectangles and text to look like a Popover). The AI relies on component instance names to map Figma elements to the correct code components. Specifically:
   - **Do not detach components.** Detached components lose their component name, and the AI cannot identify which LD component to use. If you need to customize, use variant props or overrides — never detach.
   - **Do not recreate components from scratch.** If an LD component exists for a pattern (Button, Popover, DataTable, Tabs, Tag, etc.), use the library instance. Custom look-alikes will be implemented as raw HTML instead of the proper LD component.

